📽 by @latestkruger 

An erratic elephant bullies a hoard of hippopotami after losing a contact lense in the local watering hole. 

It's no secret that hippopotamus are not to be messed with. They are categorized as one of the most aggressive and dangerous animals on earth, even towards other extremely menacing animals like crocodiles who live along side them. 

Luckily, super aggressive doesn't mean super dumb. Even a large group of them knows better than to mess with a pissed of pachyderm, who could presumably stuff multiple hippos into the african savannahs equivalent of a gym locker with ease. 

Near the end of the clip, the same elephant targets a baby hippo with impunity. This part alone tells you all you need to know about hippo/elephant relations, because if another animal did anything like that within range of a mother hippopotamus the response would be swift and utterly barbaric.

📽 by @carlostorresart

A common brown lemur eating baby magpies.

Add them to the already extensive list of animals that normally stick to a herbivorous diet, but will on occasion branch out and consume the flesh of another animal when the opportunity presents itself.

A few other animals that have been observed behaving in this manner include:

Deer
Cows
Hippos
Goats
Sheep
Horses

The prevailing theory behind this behavior is a nutritional deficiency in either salt, iron, protein or calcium.

Deer especially are known to go off menu when they are growing their antlers for the upcoming rut, researchers cite an increased demand for nutrients to explain the deer seeking their dietary boost.

Deer target nestling songbirds as their nests are usually on the ground and the small birds dont put up much of a fight.

Very similar to the strategy the lemur employs in this video

📽 by @latestkruger 

Hyenas pick away at an injured rhino. 

Seeing as this rhinos driver side (left) leg has seen better days, it's no wonder that the hyenas are laser focused on just him and practically ignoring the rest of the bunch. 

The cold logic employed by the aggressors here is simple: this rhino is not able bodied enough to run away, or mount as formidable a defense as the other bulls in the group. In its weakened state, the hyenas can focus on causing a death by a thousand cuts without worrying as much about repercussions. 

This would be a different story altogether if the other rhinos were to help him out in any capacity, but they seem to have him on the 'better you than me' list.

It is safe to assume that the hyenas eventually lost interest or were enticed by an easier meal and moved on, because this rhino was ultimately euthanized by veterinarians at KNP, as nothing could be done about his broken leg.

📽 via @latestkruger 

Black-backed jackal takes a marabou stork down for the 1,2,3. 

Jackals, along with foxes, coyotes, skunks, martens, raccoons and otters, meet the technical requirements to be classified as mesocarnivores. 

Mesocarnivore (meso=middle) play an essential role in the function of an ecosystem, especially in areas where apex predators have been eliminated. 

Their smaller size, along with a marked divergence in their behavior and ecology allow them to adapt and thrive in a range of habitats where larger carnivores/omnivores wouldn't. 

For those looking for an example of how easily a mesocarnivore can adjust, just look at how smoothly coyotes adapted to surviving on the outskirts of some suburban/urban human strongholds. 

For better or for worse, they integrated themselves effortlessly and are thriving where larger predators simply wouldn't be able to without setting off alarm bells. 

There are advantages to being middle management...

📽 by @latestkruger

Lions go to work on a cape buffalo. 

Lions, as formidable and capable as they are, must work as a team if they are to have any shot at taking down a cape buffalo. 

Unlike some other members of its family (domestic cattle, water buffalo) the cape buffalo's might has never been harnessed to serve humans. They remain wild, free and dangerous as ever. 

It is believed that cape buffalo have killed more big game hunters than any other african animal. Mature bulls can weigh anywhere between 500 - 1000kg (1102 - 2204lbs) and they can move it - top speed for a cape buffalo hovers around 56km/h (35mph)
Combine speed with the sheer mass of the animal, the solid homegrown helmet/horns that grow 1m+ (3.28ft) across, add to this their general predisposition for grouchy behavior and the "Black Death" moniker for cape buffalo starts to make a hell of a lot of sense. 

Yes, the lions won this round, but they had to "concentrate all fire on that super star destroyer" to get over the goal line.

📽 by @latestkruger 

Hyena finds a live cape buffalo stuck in the mud. 

Unable to move and eaten alive. As far as ways to die stack up, this has to be one of the absolute worst imaginable. 

From the perspective of the spotted hyena, it's the greatest day ever. She doesn't need to waste time or energy killing the animal, because there is little chance of injury, she just digs in and goes for it. 

Nature is unforgiving in all respects, which was the core motivation for the inception of this account. 

There are no do overs, there are no trial runs, a mistake as simple as walking in mud that is deeper than you anticipated can cost you your life, your death can be quick or it can last hours, it can sometimes last days or more when an infection takes hold. 

The suffering endured is immense and thoroughly immeasurable. For every instance we may witness where the misery is unbearable there are 1000s more that occur unseen, and some of these are just as bad or much much worse. 

The entire point of this post and ultimately this account, is to reflect on the brutality that we are fortunate enough to be removed from almost entirely, and to respect the lives of the animals that don't have a choice in the matter. 

You might see this and say it's gratuitous and unnecessary, just know that I disagree with that sentiment whole-heartedly. 

#natureismetal
#keepnaturemetal

📽 by @latestkruger 

Mother wildebeest and leopard fight over injured wildebeest calf. 

The mother's behavior might be misinterpreted as aggression towards the calf, but I believe she is trying to get the young one on its feet again so they can flee the scene. 

This was obviously in vain, but at least she tried. Some animal mothers will straight up ditch their kids and have new ones rather than risk injury/death defending the existing ones.

This might seem cold-blooded as hell, but it is ultimately the correct course of action in most cases - including this one.

📽 by @latestkruger 

Bushbuck surrounded and eventually killed by painted dogs. 

The massive home range of your average african painted dog pack spans several hundred square miles, and they're out there day-in day-out prowling for prey. 

For the sake of comparison: Houston Texas, which occupies a total land area of 600 square miles (1553km²) and supports over 2 million people, would only be large enough to support 2 large wild dog packs. 

To say they cover a lot of ground each day would be selling them short.

Knock Knock Motherf*cker
•
📽 by
@vegancobra
@kingcobraconservancy

King cobra goes seek and destroy on a spectacled cobra 

The diet of the king cobra consists primarily of other snakes.

Pit vipers, banded wolf snakes, pythons, other cobras, keelbacks, rat snakes, banded kraits, no matter how bad ass those other snakes may be, the king cobra is even more so because she straight up deletes them.

The venom of the king cobra is a potent neurotoxin, and if you are bitten, death can occur in as little as 30 minutes - cause: cardiovascular collapse.

If by chance you ever encounter one, you'll know you're in danger when you see it stand up straight and raise its signature hood. Fortunately, they very rarely bite humans, they prefer to save their venom for other snakes. 

This is not to say that they won't occasionally look for something else to eat like monitor lizards or other non-snake prey of similar stature, but they love to chow down on other danger noodles, and they are as proficient as they are lethal in that regard.

Lump in the Throat
•
📸 by @kirbymorejohn

Giant moray eel literally bit off more than it could chew when it attacked this porcupine pufferfish.

These tiny fish are famous for their ability to "blow" themselves up when attacked, by injesting large amounts of water (or air) they can expand their hyper elastic stomach, transforming into a virtually inedible ball several times their normal non-inflated proportions.

The porcupine pufferfish takes this a step further with the addition of spines on its skin, effectively making it even less appetizing.

Moray eels rely on their mouths for breathing, opening and closing them to pass water over their gills in order to extract oxygen from the sea, so this eel almost certainly suffocated before it had the opportunity to starve to death, as it was unable to open and close its mouth.

The eels second jaw (yes, they have 2. Known as the pharyngeal jaw) is lined with backward pointing teeth, making escape impossible for the puffer once those teeth were locked.

All in all, a fascinating natural case of mutually assured destruction.

#keepnaturemetal

There Goes The Neighborhood 
•
📽 by @thehuntressandhound 

A mild mannered residential street on the east side of Flagstaff AZ becomes an impromptu river bed, as it channels a wave of muddy water off into the great blue yonder. 

Flash flooding can happen for many reasons, ice jams, torrential rainfall, dam failure, but one common factor in these incredibly fast and destructive floods is the inability of the soil to absorb the water fast enough, which results in large amounts of runoff.

There are 2 main reasons for this: 

Oversaturation, which just means the soil has already absorbed the maximum allowable amount of water and is ineffective at taking on more. 

Soil that is too dry will also react in a similar way, as it often becomes so compacted that any large amount of fast moving water will just glide right across it, while the soil absorbs very little. 

Man-made building materials like asphalt and concrete are not held in high regard when it comes to their ability to absorb water, which is why they have drains and other water mitigation systems built into them. 

So it should surprise not even one person that these materials do absolutely nothing to slow down this extra large helping of Arizona mudslide from causing an outright calamity.

Pour one out for that prius

Considering the fact that it will be just about impossible to keep the wounds clean and free of infection, the smart money is on the ass to the right.

The near-perfect escape from any immediate threat just serves to open the door to a more menacing, invisible assailant, who has all the time in the world to whittle the zebra down to nothing.

Sadly, this is the harsh reality of the wild, as death seemingly waits around every corner.

node.text:
Microscopic Metal
•
📽 by @jam_and_germs

Lacrymaria olor, a vicious, predatory, single-celled organism attacking a smaller single-celled organism.

This is all happening in an area smaller than the head of a pin. This footage was magnified 200x for our benefit - the microscopic realm is a foreign one to most people (myself included) and I am thrilled to be able to share this with all of you.

Lacrymaria olor is an aquatic single-celled organism. They call ponds, puddles, rivers, lakes, oceans - basically anywhere there is water, home.

Think about it:
The next time you walk by a puddle, you might actually be right next to a primordial orgy of death. If the conditions are right, each puddle contains millions of tiny organisms, eating one another, reproducing with one another, and this entire world is extremely finite, lasting only as long as the puddle itself.

Anyway, back to the video.

Lacrymaria olor is classified as a eukaryote, they are organisms that evolved 2.1 billion years ago - if we were to look at our earth at that time, it would resemble a planet devoid of life.

These particular eukaryotes have an extendable cell neck complete with a cell mouth at the tip. Around the mouth they have toxin ejecting structures called extrusomes which fire when they are stimulated.

Its hunting method is simple: repeatedly extend the neck in different directions until it makes contact with prey - the simple act of touching usually kills smaller organisms immediately due to the extrusomes - then all that's left to do is eat.

No matter how big or small the organism may be, the ruthless struggle for existence always shines through.

Let 'er Rip
•
📸 by @alissatphotos

Spotted hyena making the most of her good fortune. 

The jaws of the spotted hyena are capable of generating 1100 pounds of force per square inch, allowing these formidable predators to literally crush up and devour the bones of their prey. 

Their bite is so strong that the skull of the spotted hyena has specialized vaulting or arching, which is a vital adaptation that protects it from buckling under the incredible force excerted by the contracting jaw muscles. 

Just imagine being so strong, that you're in danger of damaging your skeleton just by doing what you were put on this planet to do.

Simply incredible.

📽 by @latestkruger 

An erratic elephant bullies a hoard of hippopotami after losing a contact lense in the local watering hole. 

It's no secret that hippopotamus are not to be messed with. They are categorized as one of the most aggressive and dangerous animals on earth, even towards other extremely menacing animals like crocodiles who live along side them. 

Luckily, super aggressive doesn't mean super dumb. Even a large group of them knows better than to mess with a pissed of pachyderm, who could presumably stuff multiple hippos into the african savannahs equivalent of a gym locker with ease. 

Near the end of the clip, the same elephant targets a baby hippo with impunity. This part alone tells you all you need to know about hippo/elephant relations, because if another animal did anything like that within range of a mother hippopotamus the response would be swift and utterly barbaric.

node.text:
Do I Have Something In My Teeth?
•
📸 by @casonjollins 

A field mouse impaled by a great blue heron 

A beak is as close to having teeth as any modern day bird will ever get, so when fossil evidence provided by their long lost relatives (theropods) proved that their lack of chompers directly correlated to a 60% reduction in incubation time, the question "why are birds toothless" kind of answers itself. 

For most theropods, incubation time (time inside the egg) for the little ones varied between 3 - 6 months, and a lot of that time was spent developing their teeny tiny teeth. 

With such long incubation times, the parents guarding these eggs, along with the eggs themselves, were more susceptible to attack from hungry predators or other environmental threats.

Reducing the incubation time (ditching the teeth) was a crucial evolutionary step in the right direction, as it drastically cut down the waiting period between broods and allowed for easier proliferation of these species. 

They seem to get along fine without teeth anyway...

📽 by @carlostorresart

A common brown lemur eating baby magpies.

Add them to the already extensive list of animals that normally stick to a herbivorous diet, but will on occasion branch out and consume the flesh of another animal when the opportunity presents itself.

A few other animals that have been observed behaving in this manner include:

Deer
Cows
Hippos
Goats
Sheep
Horses

The prevailing theory behind this behavior is a nutritional deficiency in either salt, iron, protein or calcium.

Deer especially are known to go off menu when they are growing their antlers for the upcoming rut, researchers cite an increased demand for nutrients to explain the deer seeking their dietary boost.

Deer target nestling songbirds as their nests are usually on the ground and the small birds dont put up much of a fight.

Very similar to the strategy the lemur employs in this video

Starfox
•
📸 by @jens_cullmann

Sub-adult male lion playing with his food, a bat-eared fox. 

Interesting fact about this fox species, they are considered the only true insectivorous canid. Their favourite food is harvester termites, which can sometimes make up 80 - 90% of their diet. 

When this specific species of termite is unavailable, they broaden their horizons and search out other insects, which includes other termite species and basically any other bug in their immediate vicinity.

📽 by @ben_teton

Incredible trap cam video of a young female black bear chasing down and capturing a piglet.

Wild boars* are capable of fleeing the scene at 30mph (48.3km/h) even on rough terrain, which should give you an excellent idea of just how quick bears can move when required.

*It is difficult to make a positive ID due to the speed of the action, so I just went with my best guess.
